we were looking at John Stuart Mill's

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:39.110
and his attempt

00:00:39.110 --> 00:00:42.170
to reply

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:44.510
to the critics

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:47.850
of Bentham's utilitarianism

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:50.990
in his book Utilitarianism,  

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:53.790
Mill tries to show

00:00:53.790 --> 00:00:58.550
that critics to the contrary, it is possible

00:00:58.550 --> 00:01:03.170
within utilitarian framework to distinguish
between higher and lower

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:05.499
pleasures, it is possible to make

00:01:05.499 --> 00:01:07.520
qualitative distinctions of worth,

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:10.720
and we tested of that idea

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:12.390
with the Simpsons

00:01:12.390 --> 00:01:16.370
in the Shakespeare excerpts

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:19.480
and the results of our experiment

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:24.440
seemed to call into question

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:26.760
Mill's distinctions

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:30.480
because a great many of you

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:31.520
reported

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:33.860
that you prefer the Simpsons

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:36.550
but that you still consider Shakespeare

00:01:36.550 --> 00:01:42.270
to be the higher for the worthier pleasure

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:44.330
that's the dilemma

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:48.200
with which our experiment confronts Mill.

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:49.749
what about Mill's

00:01:49.749 --> 00:01:51.140
attempt to account

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.190
for especially weighty character

00:01:54.190 --> 00:01:59.010
of individual rights and justice in chapter
five of utilitarianism?

00:01:59.010 --> 00:02:03.810
he wants to say that individual rights

00:02:03.810 --> 00:02:05.320
are worthy

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:07.729
of special respect

00:02:07.729 --> 00:02:12.519
in fact he goes so far as to say that justice
is the most sacred part

00:02:12.519 --> 00:02:16.629
and the most incomparably binding 
part of morality

00:02:16.629 --> 00:02:19.189
but the same challenge

00:02:19.189 --> 00:02:20.729
could be put

00:02:20.729 --> 00:02:24.539
to this part of Mill's defense

00:02:24.539 --> 00:02:25.749
why

00:02:25.749 --> 00:02:27.549
is justice

00:02:27.549 --> 00:02:30.249
the chief part

00:02:30.249 --> 00:02:35.539
and the most binding part of our morality? well
he says because in the long run

00:02:35.539 --> 00:02:39.369
if we do justice and if we respect rights,

00:02:39.369 --> 00:02:40.769
society as a whole

00:02:40.769 --> 00:02:43.879
will be better off in the long run.

00:02:43.879 --> 00:02:49.189
well what about that?

00:02:49.189 --> 00:02:54.049
what if we have a case where making an exception
and violating individual rights actually will

00:02:54.049 --> 00:02:55.729
make people

00:02:55.729 --> 00:02:57.959
better off in the long run is it all right
then?

00:02:57.959 --> 00:03:00.730
to use people?

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:02.659
and there's a further

00:03:02.659 --> 00:03:03.100
objection

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:04.840
that could be raised against

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.289
Mill's case for justice and rights

00:03:07.289 --> 00:03:13.389
suppose the utilitarian calculus in the long run
works out as he says it will

00:03:13.389 --> 00:03:17.299
such that respecting people's rights

00:03:17.299 --> 00:03:21.739
is a way of making everybody better off
in the long run

00:03:21.739 --> 00:03:24.019
is that the right reason

00:03:24.019 --> 00:03:26.150
is that the only reason

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:28.939
to respect people?

00:03:28.939 --> 00:03:30.480
if the doctor goes in

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.719
and yanks the organs from the healthy patient
who came in for a checkup

00:03:34.719 --> 00:03:37.749
to save five lives

00:03:37.749 --> 00:03:41.510
there would be adverse effects in the long
run

00:03:41.510 --> 00:03:44.159
eventually people would learn about this

00:03:44.159 --> 00:03:47.099
and would stop going in for checkups

00:03:47.099 --> 00:03:49.899
is it the right reason

00:03:49.899 --> 00:03:51.589
is the only reason

00:03:51.589 --> 00:03:53.359
that you as a doctor

00:03:53.359 --> 00:03:57.239
won't yanked the organs out of a healthy
patient

00:03:57.239 --> 00:03:58.410
that you think

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:00.309
well if I use

00:04:00.309 --> 00:04:02.669
him in this way

00:04:02.669 --> 00:04:03.939
in the long run

00:04:03.939 --> 00:04:06.649
more lives will be lost?

00:04:06.649 --> 00:04:08.329
or is there another reason

00:04:08.329 --> 00:04:12.980
having to do with intrinsic respect for the
person as an individual

00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:16.109
and if that reason matters

00:04:16.109 --> 00:04:18.439
and it's not so clear

00:04:18.439 --> 00:04:20.840
that even Mill's utilitarianism

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:24.110
can take account of it

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:26.889
fully to examine these two

00:04:26.889 --> 00:04:29.879
worries or objections

00:04:29.879 --> 00:04:32.900
to Mill's defense

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:36.280
we need to we need to push further

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:37.970
we need to ask

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:42.349
in the case of higher or worthier pleasures

00:04:42.349 --> 00:04:46.249
are there theories of the good life

00:04:46.249 --> 00:04:50.930
that can provide independent moral standards

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:54.449
for the worth of pleasures?

00:04:54.449 --> 00:04:56.539
if so what do they look like?

00:04:56.539 --> 00:04:59.180
that's one question

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:02.009
in the case of justice and rights

00:05:02.009 --> 00:05:08.009
if we suspected that Mill is implicitly leaning
on notions of human dignity or respect for

00:05:08.009 --> 00:05:11.509
persons that are not, strictly speaking,

00:05:11.509 --> 00:05:13.030
utilitarian

00:05:13.030 --> 00:05:17.770
we need to look to see whether there are some
stronger theories of rights

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:19.699
that can explain

00:05:19.699 --> 00:05:21.000
the intuition

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.919
which even Mill shares

00:05:22.919 --> 00:05:24.109
the intuition

00:05:24.109 --> 00:05:31.109
that the reason for respecting individuals
and not using them

00:05:31.499 --> 00:05:32.939
goes beyond

00:05:32.939 --> 00:05:37.429
even utility in the long run.

00:05:37.429 --> 00:05:38.940
today we turn

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:39.950
to one

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:44.259
of those strong theories of rights

00:05:44.259 --> 00:05:47.620
strong theories of rights say

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:48.669
individuals matter

00:05:48.669 --> 00:05:55.559
not just as instruments to be used for a
larger social purpose

00:05:55.559 --> 00:05:59.270
or for the sake of maximizing utility

00:05:59.270 --> 00:06:00.009
individuals

00:06:00.009 --> 00:06:02.150
are separate beings with

00:06:02.150 --> 00:06:03.569
separate lives

00:06:03.569 --> 00:06:06.819
worthy of respect

00:06:06.819 --> 00:06:08.539
and so it's a mistake

00:06:08.539 --> 00:06:12.879
according to strong theories rights, it's a mistake

00:06:12.879 --> 00:06:17.449
to think about justice or law

00:06:17.449 --> 00:06:20.039
by just getting up preferences

00:06:20.039 --> 00:06:21.659
and values

00:06:21.659 --> 00:06:24.829
the strong rights theory we turn to today

00:06:24.829 --> 00:06:28.079
is libertarianism

00:06:28.079 --> 00:06:30.039
libertarianism 

00:06:30.039 --> 00:06:33.270
take individual rights seriously

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:38.149
it's called libertarianism because it says the
fundamental individual right

00:06:38.149 --> 00:06:42.469
is the right to liberty

00:06:42.469 --> 00:06:48.279
precisely because we are separate individual
beings

00:06:48.279 --> 00:06:50.409
we're not available

00:06:50.409 --> 00:06:52.389
to any use

00:06:52.389 --> 00:06:54.439
that the society might

00:06:54.439 --> 00:06:58.319
desire or devise. precisely because
we're individual

00:06:58.319 --> 00:07:01.009
separate human beings

00:07:01.009 --> 00:07:03.999
we have a fundamental right to liberty

00:07:03.999 --> 00:07:07.310
and that means

00:07:07.310 --> 00:07:08.089
a right

00:07:08.089 --> 00:07:10.129
to choose freely

00:07:10.129 --> 00:07:13.050
to live our lives as we please

00:07:13.050 --> 00:07:15.470
provided we respect other people's rights

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:17.180
to do the same

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:20.369
that's the fundamental idea

00:07:20.369 --> 00:07:21.930
Robert Nozick

00:07:21.930 --> 00:07:26.559
one of the libertarian philosophers we read 

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:29.610
for this course puts it this way

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:31.509
individuals have rights

00:07:31.509 --> 00:07:34.419
so strong and far-reaching are these rights

00:07:34.419 --> 00:07:37.879
that they raise the question of what, if anything

00:07:37.879 --> 00:07:43.389
the state may do.

00:07:43.389 --> 00:07:47.090
so what does libertarianism say 

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:47.699
about

00:07:47.699 --> 00:07:49.599
the role of government

00:07:49.599 --> 00:07:51.629
or of the state

00:07:51.629 --> 00:07:54.409
well there are three things that most

00:07:54.409 --> 00:07:58.029
modern states do

00:07:58.029 --> 00:07:58.789
that

00:07:58.789 --> 00:08:01.680
on the libertarian theory of rights

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:03.699
are illegitimate

00:08:03.699 --> 00:08:06.089
are unjust

00:08:06.089 --> 00:08:07.349
one of them

00:08:07.349 --> 00:08:09.729
is paternalist legislation

00:08:09.729 --> 00:08:13.799
that's passing laws that protect people from
themselves

00:08:13.799 --> 00:08:15.669
seat belt laws for example

00:08:15.669 --> 00:08:18.550
or motorcycle helmet laws

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:20.520
the libertarian says

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:24.310
it may be a good thing if people wear seat belts,

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:27.249
but that should be up to them

00:08:27.249 --> 00:08:28.459
and the state

00:08:28.459 --> 00:08:29.610
the government

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:33.620
has no business coercing them, us 

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:36.410
to wear seat belts

00:08:36.410 --> 00:08:38.520
by law

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:40.690
its coercion

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:43.820
so no paternalist legislation

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:45.810
number one. number two

00:08:45.810 --> 00:08:48.550
no morals legislation

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:50.670
many laws

00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:52.270
try to promote

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:54.059
the virtue of citizens

00:08:54.059 --> 00:08:56.550
or try to give expression

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:58.830
to the moral

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:00.270
values

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:03.700
of the society as a whole.

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:05.830
libertarians say that's also

00:09:05.830 --> 00:09:10.360
a violation of the right to liberty

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:16.560
take the example of, well a classic example
of legislation offered in the name of promoting

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:18.830
morality traditionally,

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:21.770
have been laws that prevent

00:09:21.770 --> 00:09:23.310
sexual intimacy

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:25.080
between

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:27.110
gays and lesbians

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:29.360
the libertarian says

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:31.110
nobody else is harmed

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:34.470
nobody else's rights are violated

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:38.130
so the state should get all of the business entirely

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:39.990
of trying to promote virtue

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:45.040
or to enact morals legislation.

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:48.220
and the third kind of law

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:49.810
or policy

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.880
it is ruled out

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:54.460
on the libertarian philosophy

00:09:54.460 --> 00:09:56.830
is any taxation

00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:58.570
or other policy

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:00.120
that serves the purpose

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:04.170
of redistributing income or wealth

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:07.860
from the rich to the poor

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:08.369
redistribution

00:10:08.369 --> 00:10:10.780
is a kind of, if you think about it

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:15.080
says libertarianists, a kind of coercion

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:19.160
what it amounts to is theft

00:10:19.160 --> 00:10:20.510
by the state

00:10:20.510 --> 00:10:22.750
or by the majority

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:25.360
if we're talking about a democracy

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:32.360
from people who happen to do very well and
earn a lot of money

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:38.590
now Nozick and other libertarians allow that
there can be a minimal state

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:41.140
that taxes people for the sake of

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:42.900
what everybody needs

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:45.110
the national defense

00:10:45.110 --> 00:10:46.360
police force

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:49.260
judicial system to enforce contracts and

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:50.920
property rights

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:53.880
but that's it.

